webview_android.notes: From version 3 to 4.3, there is a serious bug where text-rendering: optimizeLegibility causes custom web fonts to not render. This was fixed in version 4.4.

text.html#DominantBaselineProperty.name: dominant-baseline

animate.html#FillAttribute.name: fill

painting.html#FillProperty.name: fill

painting.html#FillOpacityProperty.name: fill-opacity

painting.html#FillRuleProperty.name: fill-rule

filters.html#FilterProperty.name: filter

text.html#FontFamilyProperty.name: font-family

text.html#FontSizeProperty.name: font-size
text.html#FontSizeProperty.summary: The font-size attribute refers to the size of the font from baseline to baseline when multiple lines of text are set solid in a multiline layout environment.

text.html#FontSizeAdjustProperty.name: font-size-adjust
text.html#FontSizeAdjustProperty.summary: The font-size-adjust attribute allows authors to specify an aspect value for an element that will preserve the x-height of the first choice font in a substitute font.

text.html#FontStretchProperty.name: font-stretch

text.html#FontVariantProperty.name: font-variant

text.html#FontWeightProperty.name: font-weight

text.html#GlyphOrientationHorizontalProp.name: glyph-orientation-horizontal

text.html#GlyphOrientationVerticalProper.name: glyph-orientation-vertical

painting.html#ImageRenderingProperty.name: image-rendering
painting.html#ImageRenderingProperty.summary: The image-rendering attribute provides a hint to the browser about how to make speed vs. quality tradeoffs as it performs image processing.

filters.html#LightingColorProperty.name: lighting-color

filters.html#LightingColorProperty.title: lighting-color

painting.html#MarkerEndProperty.name: marker-end

painting.html#MarkerEndProperty.name: marker-mid

painting.html#MarkerStartProperty.name: marker-start

painting.html#MarkerStartProperty.title: marker-start

masking.html#OpacityProperty.name: opacity
masking.html#OpacityProperty.summary: The opacity attribute specifies the transparency of an object or of a group of objects, that is, the degree to which the background behind the element is overlaid.

masking.html#OverflowProperty.name: overflow

painting.html#ShapeRenderingProperty.name: shape-rendering

pservers.html#StopColorProperty.name: stop-color

pservers.html#StopOpacityProperty.title: stop-opacity

painting.html#StrokeProperty.name: stroke

painting.html#StrokeProperty.title: stroke

painting.html#StrokeDasharrayProperty.name: stroke-dasharray
painting.html#StrokeDasharrayProperty.summary: The stroke-dasharray attribute is a presentation attribute defining the pattern of dashes and gaps used to paint the outline of the shape;
painting.html#StrokeDasharrayProperty.title: stroke-dasharray

painting.html#StrokeDashoffsetProperty.name: stroke-dashoffset
painting.html#StrokeDashoffsetProperty.summary: The stroke-dashoffset attribute is a presentation attribute defining an offset on the rendering of the associated dash array.
painting.html#StrokeDashoffsetProperty.title: stroke-dashoffset

painting.html#StrokeLinecapProperty.name: stroke-linecap
painting.html#StrokeLinecapProperty.summary: The stroke-linecap attribute is a presentation attribute defining the shape to be used at the end of open subpaths when they are stroked.
painting.html#StrokeLinecapProperty.title: stroke-linecap

painting.html#StrokeLinejoinProperty.name: stroke-linejoin
painting.html#StrokeLinejoinProperty.summary: The stroke-linejoin attribute is a presentation attribute defining the shape to be used at the corners of paths when they are stroked.
painting.html#StrokeLinejoinProperty.title: stroke-linejoin

painting.html#StrokeMiterlimitProperty.name: stroke-miterlimit
painting.html#StrokeMiterlimitProperty.summary: The stroke-miterlimit attribute is a presentation attribute defining a limit on the ratio of the miter length to the stroke-width used to draw a miter join. When the limit is exceeded, the join is converted from a miter to a bevel.
painting.html#StrokeMiterlimitProperty.title: stroke-miterlimit

painting.html#StrokeOpacityProperty.name: stroke-opacity
painting.html#StrokeOpacityProperty.summary: The stroke-opacity attribute is a presentation attribute defining the opacity of the paint server (color, gradient, pattern, etc) applied to the stroke of a shape.
painting.html#StrokeOpacityProperty.title: stroke-opacity

painting.html#StrokeWidthProperty.name: stroke-width
painting.html#StrokeWidthProperty.summary: The stroke-width attribute is a presentation attribute defining the width of the stroke to be applied to the shape.
painting.html#StrokeWidthProperty.title: stroke-width

text.html#TextAnchorProperty.name: text-anchor
text.html#TextAnchorProperty.summary: The text-anchor attribute is used to align (start-, middle- or end-alignment) a string of pre-formatted text or auto-wrapped text where the wrapping area is determined from the inline-size property relative to a given point.
text.html#TextAnchorProperty.title: text-anchor

text.html#TextDecorationProperty.name: text-decoration
text.html#TextDecorationProperty.summary: The text-decoration attribute defines whether text is decorated with an underline, overline and/or strike-through.
text.html#TextDecorationProperty.title: text-decoration

coords.html#TransformAttribute.name: transform
coords.html#TransformAttribute.summary: The transform attribute defines a list of transform definitions that are applied to an element and the element's children.
coords.html#TransformAttribute.title: transform

text.html#UnicodeBidiProperty.name: unicode-bidi
text.html#UnicodeBidiProperty.summary: The unicode-bidi attribute specifies how the accumulation of the background image is managed.

painting.html#VisibilityProperty.name: visibility
painting.html#VisibilityProperty.summary: The visibility attribute lets you control the visibility of graphical elements. With a value of hidden or collapse the current graphics element is invisible.

text.html#WordSpacingProperty.name: word-spacing
text.html#WordSpacingProperty.summary: The word-spacing attribute specifies spacing behavior between words.
text.html#WordSpacingProperty.title: word-spacing

text.html#WritingModeProperty.name: writing-mode
text.html#WritingModeProperty.summary: The writing-mode attribute specifies whether the initial inline-progression-direction for a <text> element shall be left-to-right, right-to-left, or top-to-bottom. The writing-mode attribute applies only to <text> elements; the attribute is ignored for <tspan>, <tref>, <altGlyph> and <textPath> sub-elements. (Note that the inline-progression-direction can change within a <text> element due to the Unicode bidirectional algorithm and properties direction and unicode-bidi.)
text.html#WritingModeProperty.title: writing-mode

styling.html#StyleAttribute.name: style
styling.html#StyleAttribute.summary: The style attribute allows to style an element using CSS declarations. It functions identically to the style attribute in HTML.
styling.html#StyleAttribute.title: style

text.html#TextElementTextLengthAttribute.name: textLength
text.html#TextElementTextLengthAttribute.summary: The textLength attribute, available on SVG <text> and <tspan> elements, lets you specify the width of the space into which the text will draw. The user agent will ensure that the text does not extend farther than that distance, using the method or methods specified by the lengthAdjust attribute. By default, only the spacing between characters is adjusted, but the glyph size can also be adjusted if you change lengthAdjust.
text.html#TextElementTextLengthAttribute.title: textLength

text.html#TextElementTextLengthAttribute.name: textLength
text.html#TextElementTextLengthAttribute.summary: The textLength attribute, available on SVG <text> and <tspan> elements, lets you specify the width of the space into which the text will draw. The user agent will ensure that the text does not extend farther than that distance, using the method or methods specified by the lengthAdjust attribute. By default, only the spacing between characters is adjusted, but the glyph size can also be adjusted if you change lengthAdjust.
text.html#TextElementTextLengthAttribute.title: textLength

linking.html#Links.name: a
linking.html#Links.summary: The <a> SVG element creates a hyperlink to other web pages, files, locations in the same page, email addresses, or any other URL. It is very similar to HTML’s <a> element.
linking.html#Links.title: <a>

animate.html#AnimateElement.name: animate
animate.html#AnimateElement.summary: The SVG <animate> element provides a way to animate an attribute of an element over time.
animate.html#AnimateElement.title: <animate>

animate.html#AnimateMotionElement.name: animateMotion
animate.html#AnimateMotionElement.summary: The SVG <animateMotion> element let define how an element moves along a motion path.
animate.html#AnimateMotionElement.title: <animateMotion>

animate.html#AnimateTransformElement.name: animateTransform
animate.html#AnimateTransformElement.summary: The animateTransform element animates a transformation attribute on its target element, thereby allowing animations to control translation, scaling, rotation, and/or skewing.
animate.html#AnimateTransformElement.title: <animateTransform>

shapes.html#CircleElement.name: circle
shapes.html#CircleElement.summary: The <circle> SVG element is an SVG basic shape, used to draw circles based on a center point and a radius.
shapes.html#CircleElement.title: <circle>

masking.html#EstablishingANewClippingPat.name: clipPath
masking.html#EstablishingANewClippingPat.summary: The <clipPath> SVG element defines a clipping path, to be used by the clip-path property.
masking.html#EstablishingANewClippingPat.title: <clipPath>

color.html#ColorProfileElement.name: color-profile
color.html#ColorProfileElement.summary: The <color-profile> element allows describing the color profile used for the image.
color.html#ColorProfileElement.title: <color-profile>

struct.html#Head.name: defs
struct.html#Head.summary: The <defs> element is used to store graphical objects that will be used at a later time. Objects created inside a <defs> element are not rendered directly. To display them you have to reference them (with a <use> element for example).
struct.html#Head.title: <defs>

struct.html#DescriptionAndTitleElements.name: desc
struct.html#DescriptionAndTitleElements.summary: The <desc> element provides an accessible, long-text description of any SVG container element or graphics element.
struct.html#DescriptionAndTitleElements.title: <desc>

struct.html#DescriptionAndTitleElements.name: title
struct.html#DescriptionAndTitleElements.summary: The <title> element provides an accessible, short-text description of any SVG container element or graphics element.
struct.html#DescriptionAndTitleElements.title: <title> — the SVG accessible name element

shapes.html#EllipseElement.name: ellipse
shapes.html#EllipseElement.summary: The <ellipse> element is an SVG basic shape, used to create ellipses based on a center coordinate, and both their x and y radius.
shapes.html#EllipseElement.title: <ellipse>

filters.html#feBlendElement.name: feBlend
filters.html#feBlendElement.summary: The <feBlend> SVG filter primitive composes two objects together ruled by a certain blending mode. This is similar to what is known from image editing software when blending two layers. The mode is defined by the mode attribute.
filters.html#feBlendElement.title: <feBlend>

filters.html#feColorMatrixElement.name: feColorMatrix
filters.html#feColorMatrixElement.summary: The <feColorMatrix> SVG filter element changes colors based on a transformation matrix. Every pixel's color value  [R,G,B,A] is matrix multiplied by a 5 by 5 color matrix to create new color [R',G',B',A'].
filters.html#feColorMatrixElement.title: <feColorMatrix>

filters.html#feComponentTransferElement.name: feComponentTransfer
filters.html#feComponentTransferElement.summary: The <feComponentTransfer> SVG filter primitive performs color-component-wise remapping of data for each pixel. It allows operations like brightness adjustment, contrast adjustment, color balance or thresholding.
filters.html#feComponentTransferElement.title: <feComponentTransfer>

filters.html#feCompositeElement.name: feComposite
filters.html#feCompositeElement.summary: The <feComposite> SVG filter primitive performs the combination of two input images pixel-wise in image space using one of the Porter-Duff compositing operations: over, in, atop, out, xor, and lighter. Additionally, a component-wise arithmetic operation (with the result clamped between [0..1]) can be applied.
filters.html#feCompositeElement.title: <feComposite>

filters.html#feConvolveMatrixElement.name: feConvolveMatrix
filters.html#feConvolveMatrixElement.summary: The <feConvolveMatrix> SVG filter primitive applies a matrix convolution filter effect. A convolution combines pixels in the input image with neighboring pixels to produce a resulting image. A wide variety of imaging operations can be achieved through convolutions, including blurring, edge detection, sharpening, embossing and beveling.
filters.html#feConvolveMatrixElement.title: <feConvolveMatrix>

filters.html#feDiffuseLightingElement.name: feDiffuseLighting
filters.html#feDiffuseLightingElement.summary: The <feDiffuseLighting> SVG filter primitive lights an image using the alpha channel as a bump map. The resulting image, which is an RGBA opaque image, depends on the light color, light position and surface geometry of the input bump map.
filters.html#feDiffuseLightingElement.title: <feDiffuseLighting>

filters.html#feDisplacementMapElement.name: feDisplacementMap
filters.html#feDisplacementMapElement.summary: The <feDisplacementMap> SVG filter primitive uses the pixel values from the image from in2 to spatially displace the image from in.
filters.html#feDisplacementMapElement.title: <feDisplacementMap>

filters.html#feDistantLightElement.name: feDistantLight
filters.html#feDistantLightElement.summary: The <feDistantLight> filter primitive defines a distant light source that can be used within a lighting filter primitive: <feDiffuseLighting> or <feSpecularLighting>.
filters.html#feDistantLightElement.title: <feDistantLight>

filters.html#feFloodElement.name: feFlood
filters.html#feFloodElement.summary: The <feFlood> SVG filter primitive fills the filter subregion with the color and opacity defined by flood-color and flood-opacity.
filters.html#feFloodElement.title: <feFlood>

filters.html#feFuncAElement.name: feFuncA
filters.html#feFuncAElement.summary: The <feFuncA> SVG filter primitive defines the transfer function for the alpha component of the input graphic of its parent <feComponentTransfer> element.
filters.html#feFuncAElement.title: <feFuncA>

filters.html#feFuncBElement.name: feFuncB
filters.html#feFuncBElement.summary: The <feFuncB> SVG filter primitive defines the transfer function for the blue component of the input graphic of its parent <feComponentTransfer> element.
filters.html#feFuncBElement.title: <feFuncB>

filters.html#feFuncGElement.name: feFuncG
filters.html#feFuncGElement.summary: The <feFuncG> SVG filter primitive defines the transfer function for the green component of the input graphic of its parent <feComponentTransfer> element.
filters.html#feFuncGElement.title: <feFuncG>

filters.html#feFuncRElement.name: feFuncR
filters.html#feFuncRElement.summary: The <feFuncR> SVG filter primitive defines the transfer function for the red component of the input graphic of its parent <feComponentTransfer> element.
filters.html#feFuncRElement.title: <feFuncR>

filters.html#feGaussianBlurElement.name: feGaussianBlur
filters.html#feGaussianBlurElement.summary: The <feGaussianBlur> SVG filter primitive blurs the input image by the amount specified in stdDeviation, which defines the bell-curve.
filters.html#feGaussianBlurElement.title: <feGaussianBlur>

filters.html#feImageElement.name: feImage
filters.html#feImageElement.summary: The <feImage> SVG filter primitive fetches image data from an external source and provides the pixel data as output (meaning if the external source is an SVG image, it is rasterized.)
filters.html#feImageElement.title: <feImage>

filters.html#feMergeElement.name: feMerge
filters.html#feMergeElement.summary: The <feMerge> SVG element allows filter effects to be applied concurrently instead of sequentially. This is achieved by other filters storing their output via the result attribute and then accessing it in a <feMergeNode> child.
filters.html#feMergeElement.title: <feMerge>

filters.html#feMergeNodeElement.name: feMergeNode
filters.html#feMergeNodeElement.summary: The feMergeNode takes the result of another filter to be processed by its parent <feMerge>.
filters.html#feMergeNodeElement.title: <feMergeNode>

filters.html#feMorphologyElement.name: feMorphology
filters.html#feMorphologyElement.summary: The <feMorphology> SVG filter primitive is used to erode or dilate the input image. Its usefulness lies especially in fattening or thinning effects.
filters.html#feMorphologyElement.title: <feMorphology>

filters.html#feOffsetElement.name: feOffset
filters.html#feOffsetElement.summary: The <feOffset> SVG filter primitive allows to offset the input image. The input image as a whole is offset by the values specified in the dx and dy attributes.
filters.html#feOffsetElement.title: <feOffset>

filters.html#fePointLightElement.name: fePointLight
filters.html#fePointLightElement.summary: The <fePointLight> filter primitive defines a light source which allows to create a point light effect. It that can be used within a lighting filter primitive: <feDiffuseLighting> or <feSpecularLighting>.
filters.html#fePointLightElement.title: <fePointLight>

filters.html#feSpecularLightingElement.name: feSpecularLighting
filters.html#feSpecularLightingElement.summary: The <feSpecularLighting> SVG filter primitive lights a source graphic using the alpha channel as a bump map. The resulting image is an RGBA image based on the light color. The lighting calculation follows the standard specular component of the Phong lighting model. The resulting image depends on the light color, light position and surface geometry of the input bump map. The result of the lighting calculation is added. The filter primitive assumes that the viewer is at infinity in the z direction.
filters.html#feSpecularLightingElement.title: <feSpecularLighting>

filters.html#feSpotLightElement.name: feSpotLight
filters.html#feSpotLightElement.summary: The <feSpotLight> SVG filter primitive defines a light source which allows to create a spotlight effect. It that can be used within a lighting filter primitive: <feDiffuseLighting> or <feSpecularLighting>.
filters.html#feSpotLightElement.title: <feSpotLight>

filters.html#feTileElement.name: feTile
filters.html#feTileElement.summary: The <feTile> SVG filter primitive allows to fill a target rectangle with a repeated, tiled pattern of an input image. The effect is similar to the one of a <pattern>.
filters.html#feTileElement.title: <feTile>

filters.html#feTurbulenceElement.name: feTurbulence
filters.html#feTurbulenceElement.summary: The <feTurbulence> SVG filter primitive creates an image using the Perlin turbulence function. It allows the synthesis of artificial textures like clouds or marble. The resulting image will fill the entire filter primitive subregion.
filters.html#feTurbulenceElement.title: <feTurbulence>

filters.html#FilterElement.name: filter
filters.html#FilterElement.summary: The <filter> SVG element defines a custom filter effect by grouping atomic filter primitives. It is never rendered itself, but must be used by the filter attribute on SVG elements, or the filter CSS property for SVG/HTML elements.
filters.html#FilterElement.title: <filter>

extend.html#ForeignObjectElement.name: foreignObject
extend.html#ForeignObjectElement.summary: The <foreignObject> SVG element includes elements from a different XML namespace. In the context of a browser, it is most likely (X)HTML.
extend.html#ForeignObjectElement.title: <foreignObject>

struct.html#Groups.name: g
struct.html#Groups.summary: The <g> SVG element is a container used to group other SVG elements.
struct.html#Groups.title: <g>

struct.html#ImageElement.name: image
struct.html#ImageElement.summary: The <image> SVG element includes images inside SVG documents. It can display raster image files or other SVG files.
struct.html#ImageElement.title: <image>

shapes.html#LineElement.name: line
shapes.html#LineElement.summary: The <line> element is an SVG basic shape used to create a line connecting two points.
shapes.html#LineElement.title: <line>

pservers.html#LinearGradients.name: linearGradient
pservers.html#LinearGradients.summary: The <linearGradient> element lets authors define linear gradients that can be applied to fill or stroke of graphical elements.
pservers.html#LinearGradients.title: <linearGradient>

painting.html#MarkerElement.name: marker
painting.html#MarkerElement.summary: The <marker> element defines the graphic that is to be used for drawing arrowheads or polymarkers on a given <path>, <line>, <polyline> or <polygon> element.
painting.html#MarkerElement.title: <marker>

masking.html#Masking.name: mask
masking.html#Masking.summary: The <mask> element defines an alpha mask for compositing the current object into the background. A mask is used/referenced using the mask property.
masking.html#Masking.title: <mask>

metadata.html#MetadataElement.name: metadata
metadata.html#MetadataElement.summary: The <metadata> SVG element adds metadata to SVG content. Metadata is structured information about data. The contents of <metadata> should be elements from other XML namespaces such as RDF, FOAF, etc.
metadata.html#MetadataElement.title: <metadata>

animate.html#MPathElement.name: mpath
animate.html#MPathElement.summary: The <mpath> sub-element for the <animateMotion> element provides the ability to reference an external <path> element as the definition of a motion path.
animate.html#MPathElement.title: <mpath>

paths.html#PathElement.name: path
paths.html#PathElement.summary: The <path> SVG element is the generic element to define a shape. All the basic shapes can be created with a path element.
paths.html#PathElement.title: <path>

pservers.html#Patterns.name: pattern
pservers.html#Patterns.summary: The <pattern> element defines a graphics object which can be redrawn at repeated x- and y-coordinate intervals ("tiled") to cover an area.
pservers.html#Patterns.title: <pattern>

shapes.html#PolygonElement.name: polygon
shapes.html#PolygonElement.summary: The <polygon> element defines a closed shape consisting of a set of connected straight line segments. The last point is connected to the first point.
shapes.html#PolygonElement.title: <polygon>

shapes.html#PolylineElement.name: polyline
shapes.html#PolylineElement.summary: The <polyline> SVG element is an SVG basic shape that creates straight lines connecting several points. Typically a polyline is used to create open shapes as the last point doesn't have to be connected to the first point. For closed shapes see the <polygon> element.
shapes.html#PolylineElement.title: <polyline>

pservers.html#RadialGradients.name: radialGradient
pservers.html#RadialGradients.summary: The <radialGradient> element lets authors define radial gradients that can be applied to fill or stroke of graphical elements.
pservers.html#RadialGradients.title: <radialGradient>

shapes.html#RectElement.name: rect
shapes.html#RectElement.summary: The <rect> element is a basic SVG shape that draws rectangles, defined by their position, width, and height. The rectangles may have their corners rounded.
shapes.html#RectElement.title: <rect>

script.html#ScriptElement.name: script
script.html#ScriptElement.summary: The SVG script element allows to add scripts to an SVG document.
script.html#ScriptElement.title: <script>

animate.html#SetElement.name: set
animate.html#SetElement.summary: The SVG <set> element provides a simple means of just setting the value of an attribute for a specified duration.
animate.html#SetElement.title: <set>

pservers.html#GradientStops.name: stop
pservers.html#GradientStops.summary: The SVG <stop> element defines a color and its position to use on a gradient. This element is always a child of a <linearGradient> or <radialGradient> element.
pservers.html#GradientStops.title: <stop>

styling.html#StyleElement.name: style
styling.html#StyleElement.summary: The SVG <style> element allows style sheets to be embedded directly within SVG content.
styling.html#StyleElement.title: <style>

struct.html#NewDocument.name: svg
struct.html#NewDocument.summary: The svg element is a container that defines a new coordinate system and viewport. It is used as the outermost element of SVG documents, but it can also be used to embed an SVG fragment inside an SVG or HTML document.
struct.html#NewDocument.title: <svg>

struct.html#SwitchElement.name: switch
struct.html#SwitchElement.summary: The <switch> SVG element evaluates any requiredFeatures, requiredExtensions and systemLanguage attributes on its direct child elements in order, and then renders the first child where these attributes evaluate to true.
struct.html#SwitchElement.title: <switch>

struct.html#SymbolElement.name: symbol

text.html#TextElement.name: text
text.html#TextElement.summary: The SVG <text> element draws a graphics element consisting of text. It's possible to apply a gradient, pattern, clipping path, mask, or filter to <text>, like any other SVG graphics element.

text.html#TextPathElement.name: textPath
text.html#TextPathElement.summary: To render text along the shape of a <path>, enclose the text in a <textPath> element that has an href attribute with a reference to the <path> element.

struct.html#UseElement.name: use
